Stress and Lifestyle Factors Analysis¶

This project analyzes the correlations between stress levels and various lifestyle factors using a dataset titled "Sleep_health_and_lifestyle_dataset.csv."

Project Overview¶

The primary goal of this project is to explore how different lifestyle factors, such as sleep duration, quality of sleep, exercise levels, heart rate, and daily steps correlate with stress levels.

Results¶

The final output of the analysis includes:

  • Visualizations that illustrate the distribution and relationships between different lifestyle factors and stress levels.
  • A correlation matrix that quantifies how strongly each factor is correlated with stress levels.
  • A summary that highlights which lifestyle factors are most strongly associated with stress levels, offering insights into how lifestyle choices might impact stress.

Acknowledgments¶

The dataset used in this project was sourced from kaggle.com. Inspiration for this project came from the intersection of data analysis and mental health.

In [18]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.histplot(health_df['Sleep Duration'].dropna(), bins=20, kde=True, color='skyblue')
plt.title('Distribution of Sleep Duration')
plt.xlabel('Sleep Duration (Hours)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

Most individuals in the dataset sleep between 6 and 7.7 hours, with peaks around 6.5 and 7.7 hours, suggesting two main patterns of sleep duration. This could reflect different lifestyle habits or occupational demands among participants.

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=health_df, x='Occupation', y='Sleep Duration')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.title('Sleep Duration by Occupation')
plt.ylabel('Sleep Duration (Hours)')
plt.xlabel('Occupation')
plt.show()

Sleep duration varies noticeably by occupation. Scientists and sales reps tend to have shorter sleep durations with little variation, while doctors and nurses show a wider range. Lawyers, accountants, and software engineers tend to sleep longer and more consistently. These patterns may reflect the demands and schedules typical of each profession.

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=health_df, x='Quality of Sleep', y='Stress Level')
plt.title('Stress Level by Quality of Sleep')
plt.show()

Stress levels appear to decrease steadily as sleep quality improves. Individuals with poor sleep quality (4-6) consistently report high stress levels (7-8). In contrast, those with excellent sleep quality (8-9) report much lower stress levels (3-5). This suggests a strong inverse relationship between sleep quality and stress.

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(data=health_df, x='Sleep Disorder', y='Quality of Sleep', estimator='mean')
plt.title('Average Quality of Sleep by Sleep Disorder')
plt.show()

Individuals without a sleep disorder report the highest and most consistent sleep quality. Both sleep apnea and insomnia are associated with lower sleep quality, with insomnia showing the worst average. The skewed distributions suggest that while some individuals with disorders manage decent sleep, the majority experience notably worse quality.

In [24]:
sns.histplot(health_df['Daily Steps'], kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Daily Steps')
plt.show()

Daily step counts cluster heavily between 5,000 and 7,500, with a sharp peak at 7,500 steps, suggesting it's a common activity target. There's a drop-off between 8,000 and 9,500 steps, which may reflect user behavior, tracking habits, or common goal threshholds. Very high or low step counts are rare.

In [26]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.boxplot(data=health_df, x='Stress Level', y='Sleep Duration')
plt.title('Sleep Duration by Stress Level')
plt.xlabel('Stress Level')
plt.ylabel('Sleep Duration (Hours)')
plt.show()

There is a clear inverse relationship between stress level and sleep duration. Individuals reporting stress levels (especially stress level 3) tend to get significantly more sleep, with a median of 8.2 hours. As stress level increases, sleep duration steadily declines. Those with the highest stress (level 8) average around 6 hours of sleep. This suggests that higher stress may contribute to or result from insufficient sleep.

In [27]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))

plt.title('Physical Activity Level by Stress Level')

plt.ylabel('Physical Activity Level')

Physical activity levels vary across stress groups, but individuals with higher stress (levels 7-8) tend to have lower and less consistent activity. Stress level 7 shows a sharp decline in activity with minimal variation, while level 8 shows a wide spread but low median. In contrast, moderate stress levels (5-6) are associated with higher and more stable activity levels, suggesting a possible buffering effect of regular activity against stress.

In [36]:

plt.title('Heart Rate by Stress Level')
plt.xlabel('Stress Level')
plt.ylabel('Heart Rate (BPM)')
plt.show()

The violin plot suggests a positive correlation between stress level and heart rate. Lower stress levels (3-5) show more moderate and consistent heart rates, while higher stress levels (6-8) are associated with increased heart rate and greater variability. This supports existing research linking elevated stress with sympathetic nervous system activation and higher resting heart rates.

In [37]:

plt.show()

The scatter plot reveals that both very high and very low physical activity levels are associated with longer sleep durations in low-stress individuals, while high-stress individuals consistenly report shorter sleep regardless of their activity level. Mid-level activity is more commonly linked with higher stress levels. This suggests that stress may disrupt sleep even when physical activity level is high, and that managing stress may be more important than activity level alone for improving sleep quality.

Age and Stress Level (-0.422344):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a moderate negative correlation between Age and Stress Level. Interpretation: As Age increases, Stress Level tends to decrease moderately. Younger individuals may experience higher stress levels compared to older individuals. This is consistent with the visualization showing that older individuals tend to report lower stress levels, further highlighting the potential role of age in stress management.

Sleep Duration and Stress Level (-0.811023):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a strong negative correlation between Sleep Duration and Stress Level. Interpretation: As Sleep Duration increases, Stress Level tends to decrease significantly. Individuals who sleep longer may experience lower stress levels. The visualizations also show that individuals with the best sleep patterns tend to report lower stress levels, supporting this correlation. Longer sleep duration appears to be a key factor in stress reduction.

Quality of Sleep and Stress Level (-0.898752):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a very strong negative correlation between Quality of Sleep and Stress Level. Interpretation: As the Quality of Sleep improves, Stress Level tends to decrease considerably. This suggests that individuals with higher-quality sleep tend to experience lower stress levels. This finding is further supported by the visualization of occupations with the best sleep, showing that certain occupations tend to correlate with better sleep and lower stress levels.

Physical Activity Level and Stress Level (-0.034134):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a very weak negative correlation between Physical Activity Level and Stress Level. Interpretation: There is almost no relationship between Physical Activity Level and Stress Level based on this correlation. The scatter plot visualizations show that physical activity levels are more spread out across stress levels, with little indication that increased physical activity significantly impacts stress levels in this dataset. This suggests that factors like sleep quality may play a more prominent role in stress reduction.

Heart Rate and Stress Level (0.670026):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a moderate positive correlation between Heart Rate and Stress Level. Interpretation: As Heart Rate increases, Stress Level tends to increase moderately. Individuals with higher heart rates may experience higher stress levels. The violin plot shows a wider distribution of heart rates at higher stress levels, supporting the idea that physiological responses (like heart rate) are more variable under stress, and this variability might increase as stress levels rise.

Daily Steps and Stress Level (0.186829):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a weak positive correlation between Daily Steps and Stress Level. Interpretation: There is a slight tendency for Stress Level to increase slightly as Daily Steps increase. However, the correlation is relatively weak, suggesting that the relationship between Daily Steps and Stress Level is not very strong. The scatter plot of physical activity vs. stress further indicates that while activity levels vary, they don’t strongly correlate with stress, reinforcing the idea that other factors, such as sleep, might have a more significant impact.
